# Python Coding Standards

## Style and Conventions

- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines strictly
- Use type hints (annotations) for all function parameters and return values
- Use descriptive variable names (no single letters except for loops/comprehensions)
- Prefer `snake_case` for functions and variables, `PascalCase` for classes
- Maximum line length: 88 characters (Black/Ruff default)

## Type Hints

- Always add type hints to function signatures: `def func(x: int) -> str:`
- Use modern Python type syntax: `list[str]`, `dict[str, int]` (Python 3.9+)
- Import from `typing` when needed: `Optional`, `Union`, `Literal`, `Callable`, etc.
- Avoid using `Any` unless absolutely necessary

## Error Handling

- Implement proper exception handling with try/except blocks
- Use specific exception types (ValueError, TypeError, etc.) not bare `except:`
- Always provide meaningful error messages
- Don't suppress errors silently

## Code Style

- Use list/dict comprehensions when they improve readability
- Prefer f-strings for string formatting: `f"Hello {name}"`
- Use context managers (`with` statements) for resource management
- Follow the principle of least surprise
- Use early returns to reduce nesting

## General Principles

- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Keep functions small and focused (single responsibility)
- Avoid deep nesting (max 3-4 levels)
- Use early returns to reduce complexity
- Implement proper input validation

## Error Handling

- Always handle errors gracefully
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Log errors appropriately
- Don't suppress errors silently
- Use specific exception types when available
